Life on the edge!
We hope that Jeff, Jeri, Atlas, and their fur babies NEVER need our products, but they have them “just in case” !

from @thisisironclad
•
Giving fear the middle finger.

In this episode, meet Jeff, a former Navy SEAL, and his wife, Jeri, a physician assistant, who move to Alaska to start a new life on their own homestead. 

Along with their team of sled dogs, Jeff and Jeri embark on a journey north of the Arctic Circle in pursuit of the Porcupine caribou herd to try and fill the freezer for the year.

New episodes every week.

node.text: Whether negligence is involved, or just a freak accident, we all know anything can happen on the water. The question is, will you be prepared to save a life? Could be an accident on your boat, a situation 50 miles offshore, or a problem that you just so happened to be first on the scene. Will you be ready? It’s something as mariners we all don’t think about as much as we should, and I’m here to raise awareness so you as the captain will be ready to save a life. We teamed up with @northamericanrescue and @pelicanprofessional to help provide all captains with the best and most affordable Qualified Captain Trauma Kit. It is specifically dialed in with the medical equipment you will need for when things go south. I treat these kits like an EPIRB. I don’t leave with out one whether it’s my boat, a friends boat, or a commercial boat. More information about the kits are on our website. Go check them out today, and always be prepared. Thank you @djstruntz @northamericanrescue and @pelicanprofessional to help make this happen. At the end of the day, we all want to have a good time and make it home safe. Have a great week everyone. #qualified #qualifiedcaptaintraumakits #beprepared #savealife #northamericanrescue #pelicancase #collobration

node.text:
Good people doing great things…
from @warjew.actual
•
Hanging with some PJ homies after some really long days and nights. Stopped to take a photo for the memories.

*EDIT* 
I want to take a second and illustrate just how bad ass these dudes and the entire military medical community actually is. Over 30000 people showed up over the course of like 10 days. Some had gunshot wounds, some had shrapnel wounds, many had been standing up to their hips in raw sewage. Everyone had scrapes, cuts and bruises. There were broken bones, failing kidneys and contagious disease. most were severely dehydrated/starving. There were several live births. A baby was literally born dead in the toilet of a C-17. They managed to save both the mother, and bring the baby back to life. They did not lose a single person out of HKIA. Not one human being died in their care. These people, all of them, are fucking miracle workers and i have no words to express the magnificent professionalism and dedication I saw on display everywhere these past few weeks. I am not going to comment on whose fault this is or what happened or place blame, though from where I'm sitting there are plenty of people who should be held accountable for this debacle. But, i will forever stand astonished by the quality of these people, their fundamental ability, and i will forever be thankful to my god for the opportunity to count myself among them, and to help in my own, small way.
 #afghanistan #evacuation #usmilitary #sof #gsmsg #globalsurgicalandmedicalsupportgroup #doctorswithoutborderswithguns #specialoperations #specialforces #deoppressoliber #DOL #wewillfindawayormakeone #wewillkeepthefaith #pararescue

Fair winds and following seas Max 🙏🏼🇺🇸💔

A funeral procession for U.S. Navy Corpsman Maxton Soviak was held Wednesday morning in his hometown of Berlin Heights, Ohio. Dozens of people were seen lining the streets as an American flag was also draped along the highway in his honor. 
 
The 22-year-old was one of the 13 U.S. service members killed in the airport suicide bombing in Afghanistan's capital Kabul last month and was posthumously awarded the Purple Heart. The other service members who died will be given the military medal, as well; one has already been awarded it.
 
Soviak enlisted in September 2017 and was assigned to the 1st Marine Regiment, 1st Marine Division, and based in Camp Pendleton, California. He served as a hospital corpsman, or medic. He is survived by his mother, father and 12 brothers and sisters. #navy #usa #america #servicemember #purpleheart #berlinheights #ohio #savinglives #corpsman #honorthefallen

Photo by North American Rescue on September 08, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'RECENT EVENTS ALL OVER THE GLOBE HAVE REMINDED US PAINFULLY, THAT IN CASES OF CIVIL UNREST AND NATURAL AS WELL AS MAN-MADE DISASTER, A DISPROPORTION BETWEEN THE LARGE AMOUNTS OF CASUALTIES AND THE FEW MEDICAL PROVIDERS IS VERY LIKELY UNDER TODAY'S CONDITIONS. SOCEUR (US SPECIAL OPERATIONS COMMAND EUROPE) CONDUCTED VARIOUS EXERCISE IN EASTERN EUROPEAN AREAS OF OPERATIONS AND CONCLUDED THAT CURRENT CONCEPTS AND METRICS FOR ESTABLISHING SOF MEDICAL SUPPORT FOR FRIENDLY GUERILLA FORCES IN DENIED AREAS IS NEITHER FEASIBLE NOR SURVIVABLE.'.
Photo by North American Rescue on September 08, 2021. May be an image of text.

Photo by North American Rescue on September 08, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'BASIC SKILLS: HEMORRHAGE CONTROL (PRESSURE APPLICATION, TOURNIQUET, WOUND PACKING, BANDAGING) AIRWAY MANEUVERS (RECOVERY POSITION, HEAD TILT/CHIN LIFT/JAW THRUST MANEUVER, SIT UP POSITION) RESPIRATION (ASSESSMENT OF RESPIRATORY STATUS, IDENTIFICATION OF PNEUMOTHORAX, CHEST SEAL APPLICATION) CIRCULATION (IDENTIFICATION OF SHOCK, GIVING PO FLUIDS IF POSSIBLE) HYPOTHERMIA (ACTIVE AND PASSIVE HYPOTHERMIA PREVENTION MEASURES) THESE SKILLS SHOULD BE TRAINED AND ASSESSED UNDER THE SUPERVISION FROM A QUALIFIED INSTRUCTOR. WE HAVE A 'BEGINNERS READING LIST" THAT WILL HELP BEGINNERS WITH UNDERSTANDING THE BASIC CONCEPTS. LINK IN BIO'.

Photo by North American Rescue on September 08, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'ADVANCED GUERILLA FIRST RESPONDER: ADVANCED FIRST AID PROVIDERS THAT ARE INBETWEEN REGULAR FIRST AID PROVIDERS AND EMTS IN TERMS OF SKILLS USUALLY HAVE A SIGNIFICANT IMPACT ON THE EFFECTIVENESS OF THE MEDICAL SYSTEM IN UNCONVENTIONAL SCENARIOS. SUCH CONCEPTS HAVE ALREADY BEEN SUCCESSFULLY EPLOYED IN VARIOUS EUROPEAN AND NATO ALLIED MILITARIES AS WELL AS IRREGULAR FORCES IN THE PAST. THE PURPOUSE OF THESE PROVIDERS IS TO ENHANCE POINT-OF-INJURY CARE BY SATURATING THE COMBAT FORCE AND NON-COMBATTANT SUPPORT TEAMS WITH HIGHER MEDICAL CAPABILITIES. ALSO, THEY BRIDGE THE SKILL GAP BETWEEN BASIC RESPONDERS AND PROFESSIONAL MEDICAL PROVIDERS.'.

Photo by North American Rescue on September 08, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'AGFR CURRICULUM EURMED HAS PROPOSED A TRAINING CURRICULUM FOR AN "ADVANCED GUERILLA FIRST RESPONDER" COURSE. THIS COURSE CAN BE TAUGHT BY EXPERIENCED EMERGENCY MEDICAL PROVIDERS IN IMPROVISED SETTINGS. THIS IS A PROPOSAL AND CAN BE ADAPTED TO FIT LOCAL NEEDS AND CAPABILITIES. IF YOU HAVE QUESTIONS ABOUT THIS PROJECT DM US OR JOIN OUR DISCORD FOR MORE DETAILS. LINK IN BIO ADVANCED TRAINING ADVANCED GUERILLA FIRST RESPONDER Handout Course Overview "Edition: AUG 2021 PEanmEdiCS @.M22'.

Photo by North American Rescue on September 08, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'MEDIC LEVEL PROFESSIONAL PROVIDERS ALREADY HAVE THE CAPABILITIES TO PROVIDE INITIAL PATIENT CARE AS WELL AS ADMINISTER SUSTAINMENT MEDICAL PROCEDURES. THE CYCLIC MODEL OF PATIENT CARE HOWEVER, WILL LIKELY REQUIRE PROVIDERS TO PERFORM PROCEDURES AND TAKE DECISIONS THAT WOULD CURRENTLY BE OUTSIDE THEIR SCOPE OF PRACTICE. PROVIDERS SHOULD NOT ONLY TRAIN TO ACHIEVE EXCELLENCE IN THEIR CURRENTLY PRACTICED PROCEDURES, BUT ALSO SEEK CONTINUED EDUCATION TO ENHANCE THEIR LONG TERM PATIENT CARE CAPABILITIES.'.

Photo by North American Rescue on September 08, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'FORCE MULTIPLIER ANOTHER KEY COMPONENT OF THE PROFESSIONAL PROVIDER'S ROLE IN GUERILLA SETTINGS IS MULTIPLYING THE MEDICAL CAPABILITIES OF HIS UNIT. TRAINING NEW MEDICAL PROVIDERS NOT ONLY INCREASES RESILIENCE OF THE FORCE, IT CAN ALSO BE USED AS A WAY TO GENERATE AND ENHANCE SYMPATHY BY THE GENERAL POPULATION. AS MENTIONED PREVIOUSLY, WE AT EURMED HAVE WRITTEN A COURSE CURRICULUM THAT CAN BE USED AS A GUIDELINE BY PROFESSIONAL MEDICAL PROVIDERS TO TRAIN "ADVANCED GUERILLA FIRST RESPONDERS". CHECK IT OUT.'.

Photo by North American Rescue on September 08, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'NETWORKING LASTLY, NO PERSON CAN BECOME THE ULTIMATE PROVIDER FOR ALL SCENARIOS. TO TRULY MAKE A CAPABLE AND RESILIENT MEDICAL STRUCTURE DESCRIBED IN THE FIRST POST OF THE SERIES), NETWORKING AND HUMAN RESOURCES MANAGEMENT IS ABSOLUTELY ESSENTIAL. WE GET COUNTLESS DMS FROM PEOPLE SAYING THAT THEY ARE THE ONLY MEDICAL- AND PREPAREDNESS-MINDED PERSON IN THEIR AREA. THIS IS USUALLY NOT THE CASE. TO ENABLE NETWORKING AND ENHANCE AVAILABILITY OF MEDICAL ASSETS, WE HAVE CREATED A CHANNEL ON OUR DISCORD SERVER THAT ALLOWS PEOPLE TO FIND OTHERS IN THEIR AREA TO TRAIN AND EXCHANGE INFO WITH.'.

Photo by North American Rescue on September 08, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'THIS CONCLUDES OUR MAIN SERIES ON GUERILLA MEDICINE. LET US KNOW WHAT YOU THINK IN THE COMMENTS. WE STILL HAVE MORE GUERILLA MEDICAL CONTENT TO COME. POSTS ON IMPROVISED AMBULANCES AND OTHER TOPICS ARE IN THE WORKS. IF YOU HAVEN'T YET, FOLLOW OUR PAGE @EUROPEAN_MEDICS AND CHECK OUT THE DISCORD SERVER FOR MORE CONTENT ON THIS TOPIC. LINK IN BIO'.

“Turkish spearfisherman Oğuzhan Sonugür, 33, was speared in the heart while out diving recently. It’s unknown how it happened exactly, but thanks to the Turkish members of the spearchannel community we were able to get as much of the story as we could, read below 👇🏼⠀
⠀
“Sonugür, who was taken to the shore with the help of his friends after staying at sea for a while, was taken to DEU Research and Application Hospital by 112 Emergency Service teams.⠀
Emergency room doctors, who made the first intervention in Sonugür, determined that the harpoon had entered 21 centimeters in the X-ray.

Emergency room staff of Dokuz Eylül University Research and Application Hospital prepared the patient for surgery in a race against time.⠀
⠀
Later, the patient was operated in Dokuz Eylul University Faculty of Medicine, Cardiovascular Surgery, and was taken to the intensive care unit after the difficult operation performed here.⠀
⠀
It was learned that Sonugür, who had a successful surgery, will continue to be treated at the hospital for a while”!⠀
Spearchannel

from @itisnickjones / Talons Reach Foundation
•
I am beyond grateful to be alive today. 

I am grateful for the warfighters that stood side by side with me fighting for hours on this day. 

I am grateful for the medics who strongly encouraged me to take the pain meds while we wait for the bird. 

I am grateful for our security and overwatch while we climbed back up the mountain. 

I am grateful for my family, friends, and all the support that everyone has provided me through this grueling process. 

I am grateful for my wife @hanahraejones for pushing through the long drives to Walter Reed and Arlington. And for staying by my side during the worst of times. 

I am grateful for my medical teams that have put countless hours into me to get me healthy again. 

I am just all around grateful and I wanted you all to know that. Share what you are grateful for with your loved ones or your friends tonight at dinner or when sitting on the couch. 

It is healthy to take a step back and see just how great life really is. Throw all the bullshit to the side for a minute and be present!

node.text:
@nardoctor on Axillary Junctional Bleeds. Very tough injury to treat! Very high mortality both in and out of hospital setting. YOU NEED TO KNOW YOUR ANATOMY. 
.
Anatomy- The subclavian artery is partially protected by the clavicle making it very difficult to identify where the bleed is and to control it. Proximal control is extremely difficult even in the hands of a skilled surgeon in the OR. If you feel just above the middle of your RIGHT clavicle you should be able to feel the pulse of the subclavian (the LEFT side stays deeper and cannot typically be felt/accessed) , this is the point where it dives behind the clavicle (providing an opportunity for proximal control). As it exits underneath the clavicle it becomes the axillary artery (providing the next opportunity for proximal control). Don’t forget about the subclavian vein which runs just below as it and will bleed profusely as well. 

Prehospital Control Options: YOU MUST PRACTICE THESE. 
Packing- Hemostatic gauze (like combat gauze) or X-Stat should be your initial treatment. Pack firmly and quickly while maintaining pressure and prepping a junctional. If there is massive damage, you may be able to access and compress the artery directly, otherwise pack the wound in the direction of the vessels. If no junctional available, use a pressure dressing (wrapping it under the opposite shoulder) or hold manual pressure during evac if possible. 

Foley Catheter- There have been descriptions and case studies of prehospital providers inserting a foley catheter to tamponade bleeding. In this method (for neck or axillary junctional) the foley is inserted into the entrance wound and fed to the base of the injury. The foley is then filled with saline, creating pressure inside the wound to tamponade the bleed.

Be the difference!!!
“I applied on of your tourniquets on Saturday, while on duty. A report of shots just occurred came out. Further provided information was that a male had shot himself in the leg. I was first on scene, luckily only two and a half minutes away. I ran in the house and the son-in-law is pulling on a belt trying to tighten it enough to stop the bleed, but I can see that he is still hemorrhaging profusely. I quickly deployed my CAT TQ from my duty belt and applied it high on the subjects left leg. I successfully stopped the bleed. When fire arrived on scene, and after they life flighted him out, they let me know I saved his life. The bullet entered inside left thigh, clipped his femoral and dove down and came out his calf. 9mm Federal 147gr  Hollow Point that fully expanded.”

from @uscg_rs
•
Have you heard?!? Yes. Yes, I have. Finally someone sends us some delicious footage. Great work, Sam @srea497 and crew! Not only did Sam save this guy’s life with his quick thinking, but he also implemented a basket “BADPU” because of a lack of fuel and fuel sources after the hurricane. AND this was Sam’s first live hoist. Way to go, brother. 1 life saved. SOML. We better not find out that this FM ditched the trail line, though.
Note: For the RSs, a BADPU may be necessary as a last resort, but it really sucks to get back in the cabin. “I would not recommend unless absolutely necessary.” - Sam
•
(CNN)A man was in critical condition after a shark attacked him, partially severing his leg, when he fell overboard while untangling fishing nets from a boat propeller in the Gulf of Mexico.
The Coast Guard said a medical helicopter transferred the 64-year-old man to a hospital early Friday morning after the attack 35 miles from Grand Isle, Louisiana.
The man had reportedly been untangling fishing nets from the vessel's propeller when he fell overboard and was bitten by a shark of an unknown size and species," the Coast Guard said in a news release. Crew members aboard the Moon Glow (the fishing vessel) applied a tourniquet to the man's partially amputated leg and radioed for help.
When the Coast Guard received the first radio call at 12:51 a.m., a duty flight surgeon recommended medical evacuation by helicopter.
When the helicopter crew arrived, a Coast Guard rescue swimmer administered first aid and applied a new tourniquet to the man's leg," the Coast Guard said in the press release. The crew hoisted the injured man and transported him to University Medical Center New Orleans in critical condition.
